        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "Policy: add policy file comparison command",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nAdds `openclaw policy compare` so an operator policy file can be checked against an organization-authored baseline policy file. This is policy-file conformance only: it compares policy syntax to policy syntax and does not inspect OpenClaw runtime state, evidence, credentials, or secrets.\n\nThe command is intended for lifecycle review such as \"does this workspace policy remain at least as strict as the approved baseline?\"\n\n## Usage\n\n```bash\nopenclaw policy compare --baseline official.policy.jsonc\nopenclaw policy compare --baseline official.policy.jsonc --policy policy.jsonc --json\n```\n\nExample clean JSON output:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"ok\": true,\n  \"baselinePath\": \"official.policy.jsonc\",\n  \"policyPath\": \"policy.jsonc\",\n  \"rulesChecked\": 3,\n  \"findings\": []\n}\n```\n\n## Contract\n\n`policy compare` uses the same policy rule metadata that governs scoped overlays:\n\n| Rule kind | Conformance behavior |\n| --- | --- |\n| Allowlists | Checked policy must be equal or narrower. |\n| Denylists | Checked policy must be equal or broader. |\n| Required booleans | Checked policy must keep the required value. |\n| Ordered strings | Checked policy can only move toward the more restrictive end of the configured order. |\n| Exact lists | Checked policy must match. |\n\nThe checked policy can use stricter values or add extra policy rules. A top-level checked rule can satisfy a scoped baseline rule when it is equally or more restrictive, because top-level policy applies broadly. Scope names do not need to match; scoped comparison is keyed by selector value such as `agentIds` or `channelIds` and by the policy field being checked.\n\nNew check IDs:\n\n| Check ID | Meaning |\n| --- | --- |\n| `policy/policy-conformance-invalid` | A baseline or checked policy file has invalid comparison syntax. |\n| `policy/policy-conformance-missing` | A checked policy file is missing a rule required by the baseline policy file. |\n| `policy/policy-conformance-weaker` | A checked policy file has a weaker value than the baseline policy file. |\n\nExit codes:\n\n| Command | `0` | `1` | `2` |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| `policy compare` | The policy file is at least as strict as the baseline. | The policy file is invalid, missing, or weaker than baseline rules. | Argument or runtime failure. |\n\n## Validation\n\n- CLI coverage for clean compare, missing/weaker rules, invalid files, malformed baseline syntax, scoped selector comparison, stricter top-level satisfaction of scoped baseline rules, and weaker scoped overrides.\n- Policy docs updated with compare syntax, strictness behavior, check IDs, JSON output, and exit-code behavior.\n",
